    {
      "upanishad": "mundaka",
      "verse_number": 10,
      "tags": [
        "two birds",
        "Atman",
        "Jivatman",
        "Paramatman"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "द्वा सुपर्णा सयुजा सखाया समानं वृक्षं परिषस्वजाते |\nतयोरन्यः पिप्पलं स्वाद्वत्त्यनश्नन्नन्यो अभिचाकशीति ||३.१.१||",
      "transliteration": "dvā suparṇā sayujā sakhāyā samānaṃ vṛkṣaṃ pariṣasvajāte |\ntayor anyaḥ pippalaṃ svādv atty anaśnann anyo abhicākaśīti ||3.1.1||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "द्वा सुपर्णा",
          "meaning": "two birds with beautiful wings"
        },
        {
          "word": "सयुजा सखाया",
          "meaning": "companions, always together"
        },
        {
          "word": "समानम् वृक्षम्",
          "meaning": "the same tree (body)"
        },
        {
          "word": "अन्यः पिप्पलम् अत्ति",
          "meaning": "one eats the fruit"
        },
        {
          "word": "अनश्नन् अन्यः",
          "meaning": "the other, not eating, watches"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "Two birds, companions always united, cling to the same tree. One of them eats the sweet fruit; the other, not eating, simply watches.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "द्वा सुपर्णौ — जीवपरमात्मानौ। एकः जीवः — संसारवृक्षे कर्मफलानि भुङ्क्ते। अन्यः परमात्मा — साक्षी — न भुङ्क्ते।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The two birds are the individual soul (jiva) and the supreme Self (Paramatman). The jiva eats the fruits of karma on the tree of samsara. The Paramatman is the witness — it does not eat, does not act, but simply illumines."
    },
